of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Howlett","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Hu(gh)elot</i>, a double diminutive of <i>Hugh</i>, <i>Hue</i> (see   Hugh  ) formed with the suffixes <i>-el</i> + <i>-ot</i>. This Anglo-Norman name has also been established in Ireland (Wexford) since the 13th century, where it has been Gaelicized as <b>Húiléid</b>."],"variants":[{"name":"Hollett","meanings":["English (Devon): variant of   Howlett  ."]},{"name":"Hullett","meanings":["English (Surrey): variant of   Howlett  ."]},{"name":"Hewlett","meanings":["English (Gloucestershire and Somerset): variant of   Howlett  . This surname is also established in Ireland (mainly Tipperary)."]},{"name":"Hugh","meanings":["English, Welsh, and Scottish (of Norman origin): from the Old French personal name <i>Hue</i>, from ancient Germanic <i>Hugo</i> (ultimately derived from <i>hugi-</i> ‘mind, spirit’). This was a very popular name in England after the Norman Conquest, partly due to the reputation of Saint Hugh of Lincoln (1140–1200), who was born in Burgundy and who established the first Carthusian monastery in England.","Scottish and Irish: adopted as an Anglicized form of the Gaelic personal name <i>Aodh</i>, a derivative of a Gaelic word meaning ‘fire’. See   Hughes  .","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surnames 邱 and 丘, based on their Hakka pronunciation; see   Qiu   1 and 2."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William de Howlett was born in 1438, in Bures, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom as the son of Howlett. He had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter with Katherine Wingfield. He died in 1499, in his hometown, at the age of 61."},"et":{"1438–1499":"1438–1499","1466–1525":"1466–1525","1475–1548":"1475–1548","1477–1548":"1477–1548","1478–Female":"1478–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1525":"1525","1478":"1478","1477":"1477","1499":"1499","1466":"1466","1475":"1475","ABT 1478":"umbes 1478","1438":"1438","1548":"1548","England":"England","St Mary, Newmarket, Suffolk, England":"St Mary, Newmarket, Suffolk, England","Bures, Bures-St. Mary's, Suffolk, England, UK":"Bures, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bures, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Bures, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1438–1499":"1438–1499","1466–1525":"1466–1525","1475–1548":"1475–1548","1477–1548":"1477–1548","1478–Female":"1478–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1525":"1525","1478":"1478","1477":"1477","1499":"1499","1466":"1466","1475":"1475","ABT 1478":"noin 1478","1438":"1438","1548":"1548","England":"England","St Mary, Newmarket, Suffolk, England":"St Mary, Newmarket, Suffolk, England","Bures, Bures-St. Mary's, Suffolk, England, UK":"Bures, Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Bures, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Bures, Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1438–1499":"1438–1499","1466–1525":"1466–1525","1475–1548":"1475–1548","1477–1548":"1477–1548","1478–Female":"1478–Décédée","–Male":"Décédé","1525":"1525","1478":"1478","1477":"1477","1499":"1499","1466":"1466","1475":"1475","ABT 1478":"environ 1478","1438":"1438","154